title: For Sale:  1700 Flintlock "Officer's" Rifle
postcontent:
Full stocked flintlock rifle with a 391/2"BBL (15/16" across flats). The bottom flat at the breech end is marked XV. The crown is dimpled around the bore. This was a common practice in the 18th century indicating an exceptionally good BBL.
The lock is marked W.G. Sutter, Ruffsdale, PA. This would be either the lockmaker or gun builder.
Indications are this was built sometime in the 1700's as it is still a flintlock and was never converted to percussion as many flintlocks were. The rifle is commonly called a Pennsylvania or Kentucky style flintlock and is definitely not a reproduction.

5000 Fully Processed 9mm Brass - ROLL Sized and SCHARCH Reamed

5000 Cases of Fully Processed 9mm Brass - here is what is is:

Once Fired Mixed Headstamp Brass that we purchase from a local range. The brass is hand inspected and sorted to get rid of Nickel, aluminum, steel, etc.. The brass is tumbled in stainless pins to look like new. Quick Dried in a custom built brass dryer/ "Push Through" Roll Sized to remove any bulges or inconformity such as the "Glock Bulge". Processed through a Scharch Auto Reamer processor which does the following: Identifies any non 9x19 rounds and removes them (380, makarov, 38 super etc..), Pressure checks, checks for cracked cases, decaps, REAMS (NOT SWAGE) primer pocket to remove military crimp and lastly checks for a clear primer pocket. The brass is then washed again to remove any case lube or remaining grime and to clean out primer pocket.

This brass is awesome. Loads like a dream - AND if you aren't happy you can return it for a full refund.

2000 Cases of Fully Processed 9mm Brass - here is what is is:

Once Fired Mixed Headstamp Brass that we purchase from a local range. The brass is hand inspected and sorted to get rid of Nickel, aluminum, steel, etc.. The brass is tumbled in stainless pins to look like new. Quick Dried in a custom built brass dryer/ "Push Through" Roll Sized to remove any bulges or inconformity such as the "Glock Bulge". Processed through a Scharch Auto Reamer processor which does the following: Identifies any non 9x19 rounds and removes them (380, makarov, 38 super etc..), Pressure checks, checks for cracked cases, decaps, REAMS (NOT SWAGE) primer pocket to remove military crimp and lastly checks for a clear primer pocket. title: For Sale:  Russian night vision goggles PNV-57E (ПНВ-57E)
postcontent: This is a second generation true stereo night vision device. True stereo meaning it uses two separate imaging tubes, one for each eye. It was developed during the mid 80s by the Novosibirsk instrument-making plant (Новосибирского приборостроительного завода) as a successor/update to the PNV-57. Its performance is similar to that of the US made AN/PVS-5. Produced in the Soviet Union and later on under license in Czechoslovakia, it was the most used night vision device among Soviet forces. Even today it still sees limited use within the Russian Army. Since the Soviets fought against the Mujaheddin in Afghanistan at that time, it saw its first combat use pretty quick. Initially it was reserved for helicopter pilots only, but was issued to tank crews also to replace their old PNV-57 later on. As it was mainly used by drivers and pilots the importance of the two separate tubes become clear. They allow for a stereoscopic vision, which is obviously a requirement for that sort of purpose. The squarish box worn on the back of the helmet contains a 12v or 24v transformer connected to the vehicle’s 12 or 24 volt system. However this night vision even runs with 6V or anything up to 24V. I hooked this up to a 9V battery box that is included. field of view: 30 °magnification: 1-1.2 xrefreshment rate: 35 Hzdiopter setting: +/- 4 dioptersvoltage input: 12V or 24Vvoltage output: 14kV – 19.5kVHowever the field of view is definitively more then 30°. I assume they refer to the field of view which is not obstructed by the fish-eye effect. If you have any questions email or text me at REDACTED. Thanks for looking
